Indie Game: The Movie
7.7
AdvertisementBy NICOLAS RAPOLDStruggling artists can welcome the practitioners of a new medium to their ranks, as persuasively shown by Lisanne Pajot and James Swirsky’s tenderly wrought portrait of four video game designers. A welcome primer for the uninitiated, The lucrative video game industry is already the subject of obsessive evaluation online and Before succumbing to the protracted countdown to But only the hardhearted could dismiss the vulnerable, harried and rather sweet creators of Super Meat Boy, “Indie Game” experiences a drop-off in playability after a while, losing its detailed perspective on the gamer world and on behemoths like Microsoft in favor of the diminishing returns of pressure-based narrative. But along the way comes a bracing, honest confession about these interactive creations, voiced by one designer but no doubt applying to many more makers of all kinds: “I made it for myself.”




Opens on Friday in Manhattan.
Directed by Lisanne Pajot and James
Swirsky
